|  | NPOI | IronXL.Excel |What About Other Libraries?The C# Excel ecosystem includes several alternatives beyond NPOI and IronXL:: XLSX only (no XLS support). Version 5+ switched from LGPL to a Polyform Noncommercial License that requires a commercial license for business use. EPPlus has solid documentation and a fluent API, but the licensing change in 2020 surprised many teams who had built on EPPlus 4.x's open-source license.: XLSX only (no XLS support). MIT-licensed (genuinely free). Clean .NET-style API that is closer to IronXL's design philosophy than NPOI's. Solid choice for XLSX-only projects that need a free option with modern API design.: Microsoft's official library for OOXML manipulation. Very low-level: you work with the XML structure directly, not Excel concepts. Powerful but verbose, think of it as "XML editing that happens to produce valid XLSX files." MIT-licensed.: Full-featured commercial library with broader format support than any free alternative. More expensive than IronXL, but includes charts, pivot tables, and PDF export. Enterprise-focused licensing.Each has tradeoffs. If you need XLS (the legacy binary format) plus free licensing, NPOI is your only option. If you need XLSX-only with a modern API and free licensing, ClosedXML is worth evaluating. If you need the broadest format support, LINQ integration, and dedicated support, IronXL covers that space.When Should You Choose NPOI, and When Should You Choose IronXL?Choosing a library is an architectural decision, not just a feature comparison. The right choice depends on your project's constraints, your team's experience, and your long-term maintenance strategy.Your budget is genuinely zero. NPOI is Apache 2.0 licensed, free for any use, including commercial. If your organization cannot approve any software purchases, NPOI is the most capable free option that supports both XLS and XLSX.You need XLS (legacy BIFF) format support with a free license. ClosedXML and EPPlus (free tier) only support XLSX. NPOI's HSSF implementation handles XLS files reliably.Your team has Apache POI experience. If your developers are coming from a Java background and already know POI patterns (create row → create cell → set value), NPOI's API will feel familiar.The project is a small utility or internal tool. For a script that generates one report monthly, NPOI's verbose API is an acceptable tradeoff for zero licensing cost. Many .NET global tools and internal utilities use NPOI for exactly this reason.Open-source compliance is required. Some organizations mandate that all dependencies carry OSI-approved open-source licenses. NPOI's Apache 2.0 license satisfies this requirement.Developer productivity is a priority. IronXL's API requires fewer lines, fewer null checks, and less type-switching code. For teams writing Excel logic regularly, the time savings compound.You need CSV, JSON, or XML format support. NPOI handles XLS and XLSX only. If your data pipeline involves format conversion, importing CSV feeds, exporting JSON for web APIs, or generating XML for enterprise integrations — IronXL eliminates the need for additional parsing libraries.You need LINQ integration. If your application processes Excel data as collections — filtering, grouping, aggregating — IronXL's IEnumerable ranges compose naturally with the rest of your LINQ pipeline.Documentation and support matter. For teams that need searchable documentation, getting-started guides, and a dedicated support channel, IronXL provides what NPOI's community-maintained repository cannot.You need formula evaluation beyond basic functions. IronXL's 450+ function library handles advanced formulas that NPOI's evaluator does not support.Large workbook performance matters. For applications processing 50,000+ row workbooks regularly, IronXL's memory-efficient internal representation and recent performance optimizations (5-10x faster range retrieval as of December 2024) can make a measurable difference.A pragmatic approach to this decision involves a simple calculation. Consider a team of 3 developers building a reporting module:: $0 licensing + ~4 days of learning undocumented API patterns + ongoing time debugging null reference exceptions and type-mismatch errors = estimated $4,000-6,000 in developer time over the first year.: $1,199 licensing (Plus, 3 devs) + ~1 day of onboarding with comprehensive documentation = $1,199 + ~$1,000 in developer time.The "free" library costs more in total when developer time is factored in. This is not an argument against NPOI, it is an argument for making the decision with full cost visibility.How Do You Migrate from NPOI to IronXL?If you are maintaining a project that currently uses NPOI and the limitations we discussed are affecting your team, here is a practical migration path.|  |  |
|----|----|
| new XSSFWorkbook() | WorkBook.Create() |
| WorkbookFactory.Create(stream) | WorkBook.Load(path) |
| workbook.CreateSheet("name") | workbook.CreateWorkSheet("name") |
| sheet.CreateRow(index) | Not needed (auto-created) |
| row.CreateCell(index) | sheet["A1"] or sheet[row, col] |
| cell.SetCellValue(value) | cell.Value = value |
| cell.SetCellFormula("SUM(A1:A10)") | cell.Formula = "=SUM(A1:A10)" |
| cell.CellType switch | cell.StringValue / cell.DoubleValue |
| cell.CellStyle = style | cell.Style.Font.Bold = true |
| workbook.Write(stream) | workbook.SaveAs("file.xlsx") |
| workbook.CreateCellStyle() + CreateFont() | Direct style properties on ranges |
| XSSFFormulaEvaluator.EvaluateAllFormulaCells() | Automatic on value access |
| Manual row/cell iteration for DataTable | sheet.LoadFromDataTable(dt) |
| Manual row/cell copy loop | range.Copy(targetSheet, "A1") |// BEFORE: NPOI — Generate monthly report
using NPOI.XSSF.UserModel;
using NPOI.SS.UserModel;
using System.IO;

XSSFWorkbook workbook = new XSSFWorkbook();

ISheet sheet = workbook.CreateSheet("Monthly Report");

IRow header = sheet.CreateRow(0);

header.CreateCell(0).SetCellValue("Department");
header.CreateCell(1).SetCellValue("Budget");
header.CreateCell(2).SetCellValue("Actual");
header.CreateCell(3).SetCellValue("Variance");

ICellStyle headerStyle = workbook.CreateCellStyle();
IFont headerFont = workbook.CreateFont();
headerFont.IsBold = true;
headerStyle.SetFont(headerFont);

for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++)
    header.GetCell(i).CellStyle = headerStyle;

string[] depts = { "Engineering", "Marketing", "Sales" };
double[] budgets = { 150000, 80000, 120000 };
double[] actuals = { 142000, 95000, 108000 };

IDataFormat fmt = workbook.CreateDataFormat();

ICellStyle currencyStyle = workbook.CreateCellStyle();

currencyStyle.DataFormat = fmt.GetFormat("$#,##0");

for (int i = 0; i < depts.Length; i++)
{
    IRow row = sheet.CreateRow(i + 1);
    row.CreateCell(0).SetCellValue(depts[i]);
    ICell budgetCell = row.CreateCell(1);
    budgetCell.SetCellValue(budgets[i]);
    budgetCell.CellStyle = currencyStyle;
    ICell actualCell = row.CreateCell(2);
    actualCell.SetCellValue(actuals[i]);
    actualCell.CellStyle = currencyStyle;
    ICell varianceCell = row.CreateCell(3);
    varianceCell.SetCellFormula($"B{i + 2}-C{i + 2}");
    varianceCell.CellStyle = currencyStyle;
}

using FileStream stream = new FileStream("monthly_report.xlsx", FileMode.Create);

workbook.Write(stream);
NPOI Generated Report Output// AFTER: IronXL — Same report, same output
using IronXL;

WorkBook workbook = WorkBook.Create();

WorkSheet sheet = workbook.CreateWorkSheet("Monthly Report");

sheet["A1"].Value = "Department";
sheet["B1"].Value = "Budget";
sheet["C1"].Value = "Actual";
sheet["D1"].Value = "Variance";

sheet["A1:D1"].Style.Font.Bold = true;

string[] depts = { "Engineering", "Marketing", "Sales" };
double[] budgets = { 150000, 80000, 120000 };
double[] actuals = { 142000, 95000, 108000 };

for (int i = 0; i < depts.Length; i++)
{
    int row = i + 2;
    sheet[$"A{row}"].Value = depts[i];
    sheet[$"B{row}"].Value = budgets[i];
    sheet[$"C{row}"].Value = actuals[i];
    sheet[$"D{row}"].Formula = $"=B{row}-C{row}";
}

sheet["B2:D4"].FormatString = "$#,##0";

